# type-novel

A fast, minimal typing trainer for reading novels one chunk at a time.
Built in PureScript with Deku, served by Vite. No backend required.

---

## What It Is

Most typing trainers give you pangrams and random word lists. This one
lets you type actual books — the text you've been meaning to read anyway.
Drop a `.txt` file in `public/books/`, click Load, and start typing.
Progress through the entire novel one 300-character chunk at a time.

---

## Stack

| Layer      | Technology                              |
|------------|-----------------------------------------|
| Language   | PureScript                              |
| UI         | Deku (push-based FRP, no virtual DOM)   |
| HTTP       | Affjax                                  |
| Dev server | Vite (`appType: "mpa"`)                 |
| Build      | Spago + esbuild                         |
| Nix        | Flake-based dev environment             |

No React. No TypeScript. No Node runtime in production. The compiled
output is a single JS bundle served as a static file.

---

## Performance Architecture

The central design constraint is that **no DOM nodes are created or
destroyed during typing** — only CSS class attributes are written.

```
keystroke
  → handleKeyPress (Effect, all reads from STRef — no Poll subscriptions)
  → setKS (single Poll fire)
      → N × DA.klass writes    (charClassKS per character span)
      → N × text node writes   (displayChar per character span)
      → 3 × text node writes   (stats bar)
  → browser batches into one layout pass
```

Key decisions:

- **Single `KeystrokeState` atom** — one `setKS` call per keystroke, one
  Poll propagation, no multiplied fan-out from separate setters.

- **`<#~>` used twice only** — once on chunk advance (replaces character
  spans), once on completion overlay toggle. Never on keystrokes.

- **`Data.String.CodeUnits` throughout** — `CU.charAt` is O(1) direct
  code-unit indexing. `cleanText` guarantees ASCII output so code-unit
  index equals code-point index. `CodePoints.codePointAt` would be O(i)
  per call and is never used in the hot path.

- **Delta stats** — `updateStats` examines exactly one character position
  per keystroke (the added or removed position) rather than scanning the
  full typed string. Accuracy is O(1).

- **`Array Char` pre-computed at load time** — character arrays are
  computed once in `mkExercise`/`chunkText` and stored on the exercise
  record. No allocation in the keystroke handler.

- **Rolling 10-second WPM** — newest-first ring buffer capped at 60
  entries. `Array.filter` over at most 60 elements per keystroke.
  Eliminates the spike-to-infinity that raw elapsed-time WPM produces.

- **Caret idle timer** — `isTyping` is set true on every keystroke and
  false exactly once, 500ms after the last keystroke, via a
  cancel-and-reschedule pattern using `Effect.Ref` for the `TimeoutId`.
  The CSS blink animation is suppressed while `isTyping` is true.

